at|Nowadays Jacoby transfers are just one of the many types of transfer bids used by expert players, but Jacoby transfers are the only type of transfer bids that have been embraced by average bridge players (and they are the only type of transfers in the SAYC bidding system). 

The basic concept of transfers (that is, a bid that asks your partner to bid a particular suit at a particular level) is a very powerful one. When a player invokes a transfer bid, he knows how the bidding is going to continue (at least most of the time) and this allows him to plan his next bid in advance. The fact that transfer bids tend to keep the bidding at a low level gives the player who invokes a transfer a lot of options when it is his turn to bid again.

Jacoby transfer bids are one of the most useful and effective conventions that have ever been devised, but these artificial bids are more complex than most of the conventions that are commonly used by average bridge players. Keep the following warning in mind when you learn any new convention, but be especially careful when the convention you learn has as many possible followup bids as do Jacoby transfers!

|
pg| ***** 101 ***** |


cs|4|At|^-{ Do not adopt any convention until you have thoroughly discussed its use with your partner! }

|
