|cp||at|In this chapter you have been introduced to the Standard American Yellow Card (SAYC) bidding system. In the original Learn to Play Bridge program, the bidding system that was presented was referred to as Modern Standard American with 5-card majors. That bidding system was specifically designed for teaching new bridge players about bidding. 

SAYC on the other hand is arguably the most popular bidding system in the world today. Most of the bidding sequences that were discussed in Learn to Play Bridge have the same meanings that they would using SAYC. It is the case, however, that the SAYC bidding system is different than Modern Standard American with 5-card majors in some areas. One of the main areas of difference involves responding to a 1NT opening bid. In particular, Jacoby transfer bids are used in SAYC and this convention was never mentioned in the Learn to Play Bridge program.

|
pg| ***** 156 ***** |


at|In SAYC, the 2@D and 2@H responses to a 1NT opening bid are Jacoby transfer bids:

^D{|cs|1|ia|o1n!2d|at|} ^O{|cs|1|ia|o1n!2h|at|}

|
pg| ***** 157 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ A Jacoby transfer bid promises at least 5 cards in the next higher-ranking (major) suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 158 ***** |


at|So in the first bidding sequence, the 2@D response to 1NT promises at least 5 hearts. In the second bidding sequence, the 2@H response to 1NT promises at least 5 spades.
|
pg| ***** 159 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
As we have seen, Jacoby transfers are very flexible bids that can be used when the responder to a 1NT opening has a wide variety of hand types. The only constant about the type of hands that are appropriate for Jacoby transfer bids is that the responder must always have at least a 5-card major to use one of these bids.

|
pg| ***** 160 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Jacoby transfer bids can be used with signoff hands, invitational hands, hands that are 
 strong enough to force to game, and hands that are strong enough to explore for slam. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 161 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Jacoby transfer bids can be used with balanced hands, unbalanced 
 hands, hands with only 1 long suit, or hands with 2 or 3 long suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 162 ***** |


at|The 1NT opener does not have much to think about when his partner uses a Jacoby transfer:

|
