nt|^b@2^z@3|ht|a|va|8|at|^D{|cs|1|ia|o1n2d!3h|at|} ^O{|cs|1|ia|o1n2h!3s|at|}

|cs|1|at|Super-accepting a Jacoby transfer bid can be dangerous because the responder could have a very weak hand for his transfer. That is one of the reasons why the opener should not super-accept very often - he should wait until he has both a maximum hand for his 1NT opener and 4-card support for the responder's major suit. There are 2 reasons why the opener should super-accept his partner's transfer under these circumstances:

|
pg| ***** 166 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 1) If the responder's hand was not quite strong enough to issue an invitation to game, 
 the responder might reconsider after the opener super-accepts his transfer. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 167 ***** |


cs|2|At|^-{ 2) If the responder has interest in a possible slam, the bidding will be easier for him if he 
 learns right away that his partner has a great hand in support of his long major suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 168 ***** |


at|Jacoby transfer bids are among the most popular conventions that have ever been devised. This is largely a function of how effective these bids are in practice. Here is one of the reasons why Jacoby transfers work so well:

|
pg| ***** 169 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ After a Jacoby transfer bid is used, the 1NT opener will become the
 declarer if the responder's long major suit becomes the trump suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 170 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|cs|1|at|
It may not have been immediately obvious why it is advantageous for the 1NT opening bidder rather than the responder to end up as the declarer, but we have explored this issue in some detail. This phenomena is not restricted to the bidding sequences that start with a 1NT opening bid. In general we have seen:

|
pg| ***** 171 ***** |


at|^-{ If a partnership has a choice as to which player will be the declarer, on most deals 
 it will be to their advantage to try to arrange for the stronger hand to be declarer. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 172 ***** |


at|The reason for this is that the opening lead gives the defenders a chance to attack a suit of their choice. Making the stronger hand the declarer (rather than the dummy) will often serve to protect the high cards in that hand from immediate attack.

|
pg| ***** 173 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ One of the main advantages of using Jacoby transfer bids is that these bids allow the 
 partnership to protect the 1NT opener's high cards by making him the declarer more often. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 174 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ The word transfer is part of the name of Jacoby transfer bids because these bids 
 effectively transfer the declaration from the (weak) responder to the (strong) opener. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 175 ***** |


at|Allowing the 1NT opener to be declarer on a large percentage of hands is certainly a relevant advantage to using Jacoby transfer bids, but there is an even more important reason why these bids are effective in practice:

|
pg| ***** 176 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ After the 1NT opener completes the transfer, the responder 
 is well-placed to continue describing his hand with his next bid. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 177 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|va|5|at|There are a lot of things that the responder can do after the opener completes the transfer. Fortunately the responder's rebids all mean what you would expect.

|cs|1|ht|d|va|3|at|^D{|cs|1|ia|o1n2d2h?|at| } ^O{|cs|1|ia|o1n2h2s?|at| }

|
pg| ***** 178 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ To sign off in 2 of a major after a 1NT opening bid, transfer to your 5-card 
 (or longer) major suit and pass when your partner completes the transfer. }

|
pg| ***** 179 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ A Jacoby transfer followed by a 2NT rebid describes an 
 invitational hand with exactly 5 cards in responder's major. }

|
pg| ***** 180 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ With an invitational hand containing a 6-card (or longer) major suit, transfer
 to your major and, after the transfer is completed, rebid 3 of your major. }

|
pg| ***** 181 ***** |


cs|1|at|{ A Jacoby transfer followed by a 3NT rebid shows exactly 5 cards in the major and
 asks the 1NT opener to choose between 3NT and 4 of the major as a final contract. }

|
pg| ***** 182 ***** |


cs|3|at|{ To sign off in 4 of a long major after a 1NT opening bid, transfer to your 
 major and then rebid 4 of your major (which your partner will pass). }

|
pg| ***** 183 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ A Jacoby transfer bid followed by a 4NT rebid is not Blackwood - it is a quantitative try 
 for slam that is based on a balanced hand with exactly 5 cards in the major that was shown. }
|
pg| ***** 184 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
|cs|4|at|All of responder's possible rebids after the opener completes the transfer were covered on the last page except for those that involve the rebid of a new suit. The following principle that covers this case has only 1 exception (which we will review shortly):

|
pg| ***** 185 ***** |


at|^-{ A Jacoby transfer followed by the bid of a new suit is forcing to game and describes 
 a hand with at least a 5-card major and at least 4 cards in the new suit that was introduced. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 186 ***** |


at|For some reason this rebid by the responder after a Jacoby transfer causes confusion for some bridge players. It is important to understand the following 2 points about these bidding sequences:

|
pg| ***** 187 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. A Jacoby transfer followed by the bid of a new suit does not necessarily 
 imply that the responder might have interest in playing in a slam contract. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 188 ***** |


at|Responder needs to have the strength to force to game (that is, 10 or more total points) in order to rebid a new suit after a Jacoby transfer. Many bridge players mistakenly think the responder must have slam interest in order to bid this way.

|
pg| ***** 189 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ 2. A Jacoby transfer followed by the bid of a new suit shows at least 4 cards in the new suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 190 ***** |


at|Some bridge players are under the wrong impression that when they bid this way, the new suit bid is actually a cuebid (as opposed to a possible trump suit). In other words, they might bid a new suit after their Jacoby transfer bid was completed in order to show the Ace of that suit in a hand with interest in slam. That would be a serious mistake. Responder's rebid of a new suit after a Jacoby transfer guarantees that he holds at least 4 cards in that suit.

|
pg| ***** 191 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|va|5|at|We then went on to consider how the responder should handle major 2-suiters with varying strengths and distributions after a 1NT opening bid by his partner. A major 2-suiter is any hand with at least 5 cards in one of the majors and at least 4 cards in the other major. Here are some general reminders of how the responder should select his first action with such hands:

|
pg| ***** 192 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ With less than invitational strength, the responder should transfer to his longest 
 and strongest major suit and then pass when his partner completes the transfer. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 193 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ When the responder has exactly 5 cards in one major suit, 4 cards in the other 
 major suit, and at least invitational strength, he should start by using Stayman. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 194 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ When the responder has at least 5 cards in both major suits and at 
 least invitational strength, he should start with a Jacoby transfer bid. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 195 ***** |


at|Here is a more detailed decription of how the responder should bid with 5-5 or 5-4 in the majors when he has less than enough strength to invite game opposite a 1NT opening:

|
pg| ***** 196 ***** |


cs|1|At|^-{ With 5-5 in the majors and less than invitational strength, the responder to a 1NT opening
 should transfer to his stronger major and pass when his partner completes the transfer. }

|
pg| ***** 197 ***** |


cs|4|At|{ With 5-4 in the majors and less than invitational strength, the responder to a 1NT opening
 should transfer to his 5-card major and pass when his partner completes the transfer. }

|
pg| ***** 198 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ With a weak major 2-suiter, the responder cannot afford to use Stayman because
 he will have no good rebid if the opener denies a 4-card major by bidding 2@D. }
|
pg| ***** 199 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|va|5|at|When the responder to a 1NT opening has a major 2-suiter with at least invitational strength, he can afford to investigate the possibility of playing in both major suits. 
|
pg| ***** 200 ***** |


va|7|
cs|1|At|^-{ With 5-5 in the majors and invitational strength, the responder to a 1NT opening should 
 bid 2@D to transfer to hearts and rebid 2@S when his partner completes the transfer. }
^-|
pg| ***** 201 ***** |


va|7|
at|This special sequence is the one exception to a principle mentioned earlier. In all other cases, a Jacoby transfer bid followed by the rebid of a new suit by the responder is forcing to game. In this sequence, however, the bid of a new suit by the responder (2@S) is only invitational.
|
pg| ***** 202 ***** |


va|7|
cs|3|at|^-{ With 5-4 in the majors and invitational strength, the responder to a 1NT opening should 
 use Stayman, planning to raise 2@H or 2@S and to rebid 2 of his 5-card major over 2@D. }

|
pg| ***** 203 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ With 5-5 in the majors and enough strength to force to game opposite a 1NT opening,  
 bid 2@H to transfer to spades and rebid 3@H when your partner completes the transfer. }

|
pg| ***** 204 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ With 5-4 in the majors and game forcing strength, the responder to a 1NT opening should 
 use Stayman, planning to raise 2@H or 2@S and to rebid 3 of his 5-card major over 2@D. }
|
pg| ***** 205 ***** |


va|7|
at|^-Here are some guidelines for handling other major 2-suiters after a 1NT opening bid:
|
pg| ***** 206 ***** |


va|7|
cs|1|at|^-{ With 6-5 (or better) in the majors facing a 1NT opening bid, the responder should 
 usually follow the same strategy that he would use if he had been dealt 5-5 in the majors. }

|
pg| ***** 207 ***** |


cs|2|at|{ With 6-4 or 7-4 in the majors facing a 1NT opening bid, the responder should
 usually ignore his 4-card major and treat his hand as if it was a 1-suited hand. }
^-
|
